05085nam a22007575i 9780231551397DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020025092  a97802315513977 a10.7312/mill195582doi  a(DE-B1597)566385  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995b.M5255 2021 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/752231 aMiller, D. A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSecond Time Around :bFrom Art House to DVD /cD. A. Miller. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b117 b&w film stills  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tI SECOND THOUGHTS -- t1 The Cinematheque Today -- t2 The Second Time Around -- tII SECOND TIMES -- t1 Sansho the Bailiff (1954) -- t2 Cruising (1980) -- t3 Berlin Alexanderplatz (1980) -- t4 Bonnie and Pierrot -- t5 Rocco and His Brothers (1960) -- t6 Vertigo (1958) -- t7 La Ronde (1950) -- t8 The H-Man (1958) -- t9 French Hitchcock -- t10 Toby Dammit (1969) -- t11 Chabarthes: Chabrol, Le Beau Serge; Barthes, “Cinema Right and Left” -- t12 Medea (1972) -- t13 Last Time Around: The Birds (1963) -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe art houses and cinema clubs of his youth are gone, but the films that D. A. Miller discovered there in the 1960s and ’70s are now at his fingertips. With DVDs and streaming media, technology has turned the old cinematheque’s theatrical offerings into private viewings that anyone can repeat, pause, slow, and otherwise manipulate at will.In Second Time Around, Miller seizes this opportunity; across thirteen essays, he watches digitally restored films by directors from Mizoguchi to Pasolini and from Hitchcock to Honda, looking to find not only what he first saw in them but also what he was then kept from seeing by quick camerawork, normal projection speed, missing frames, or simple censorship. At last he has an unobstructed view of the gay leather scene in Cruising, the expurgated special effects in The H-Man, and the alternative ending to Vertigo. Now he can pursue the finer details of Chabrol’s debt to Hitchcock, Visconti’s mystificatory Marxism, or the unemotive emotion in Godard.Yet this recaptured past is strangely disturbing; the films and the author have changed in too many ways for their reunion to be like old times. The closeness of Miller’s attention clarifies the painful contradictions of youth and decline, damaged prints and flawless restorations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMotion picturesvReviews. 0aMotion picturesxTechnological innovations. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2021z9783110753790oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishz978311075403208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mill1955840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231551397423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231551397/original  a978-3-11-073823-0  Art and Architecture eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 20